  <sec sec-type="intro" id="SEC1">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <p>The substantial heterogeneity observed among cancer cells, involving variations in gene expression, cell composition and immune microenvironment, presents a major challenge for accurate diagnosis and treatment (<xref rid="B1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>,<xref rid="B2" ref-type="bibr">2</xref>). However, advancements in single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) and spatial transcriptome (ST) technology offer promising new avenues to address this challenge. By enabling the dissection of cancer cell diversity at the single-cell resolution and compensating for the lack of spatial information of the source tissue, these developments can provide new opportunities for analyzing the complex nature of cancer (<xref rid="B3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref>,<xref rid="B4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>). Currently, scRNA-seq and ST have revealed the transcriptional and spatial landscapes of a wide variety of tissues under various conditions (<xref rid="B5" ref-type="bibr">5–15</xref>).</p>
    <p>With the rapid emergence of a huge number of single-cell datasets worldwide, it is imperative for researchers to be able to access and interpret large-scale cancer genomics resources. Recently established single-cell databases serve as effective tools for synthesizing and presenting vast quantities of single-cell data for research. For example, CancerSEA showcases 14 distinct functional states of cancer from 25 cancer types (<xref rid="B16" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>). TISCH2 provides gene expression visualization of 190 datasets across 50 tumor types (<xref rid="B17" ref-type="bibr">17</xref>). CancerSCEM provides 208 cancer samples across 20 cancer types (<xref rid="B18" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>). TMExplorer presents 48 tumor datasets from 30 cancer types through an R package (<xref rid="B19" ref-type="bibr">19</xref>). The Curated Cancer Cell Atlas covers 77 tumor datasets (<xref rid="B20" ref-type="bibr">20</xref>). PanC_T explores T cell data across 21 cancer types (<xref rid="B21" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>), while scAtlasLC compares malignant and non-malignant cells in liver cancer (<xref rid="B22" ref-type="bibr">22–25</xref>). </p>
    <p>To leverage cellular locations obtained from high-throughput methods such as ST (<xref rid="B26" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>), MERFISH (<xref rid="B27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>) and Visium (<xref rid="B28" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>), we constructed the Single-cell and Spatially-resolved Cancer Resources (SCAR) database, which encompasses a wide array of cancer-related resources and includes a total of 11 301 352 cells. The database includes two distinct components: SCAR_ST, a spatial transcriptomic atlas containing data from 21 tumor tissues and SCAR_Atlas, containing single-cell atlases for the 395 cancer subtypes. Additional modules were designed for screening tumor biomarkers and analyzing gene expression patterns. Through extensive analysis of publicly available cancer datasets, SCAR serves as a versatile online platform for cancer genomics, enabling users to unravel the complexities of cancer at the tissue, cell and gene levels.</p>
  </sec>
  <sec id="SEC2">
    <title>Data collection and processing</title>
    <sec id="SEC2-1">
      <title>ScRNA-seq data collection and processing</title>
      <p>To create the SCAR database, we collected scRNA-seq data from 395 cancer subtypes by manually searching publications on PubMed (<ext-link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/" ext-link-type="uri">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/</ext-link>) and obtaining publicly available and integrated datasets from multiple cancer databases, including NCBI/GEO (<xref rid="B29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>), EBI (<xref rid="B30" ref-type="bibr">30</xref>), TISCH2 (<xref rid="B17" ref-type="bibr">17</xref>), CancerSEA (<xref rid="B16" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>), CancerSCEM (<xref rid="B18" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>) and Curated Cancer Cell Atlas (<xref rid="B20" ref-type="bibr">20</xref>). We also integrated scRNA-seq datasets from a prior study (<xref rid="B31" ref-type="bibr">31</xref>), containing 1 092 172 cells from human and mouse liver cancer samples. For cell type annotation, we retained the original cell clustering and cell identity whenever the metadata was available. In cases where cell annotation information was not provided in the original paper, we assigned cell labels to each cluster based on the specific expression of canonical cell markers. To validate the annotation results, we performed Gene Ontology (GO) (<xref rid="B32" ref-type="bibr">32–34</xref>) enrichment analysis of cell type-specific genes. Briefly, we used Seurat (v4.3.0) (<xref rid="B35" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>) with parameters set to 200 &lt; nFeatures &lt; 6000 and MT &lt; 10% for cell quality control and used the ‘NormalizeData’ function to normalize gene expression matrices. We utilized the ‘FindVariableFeatures’ function to identify highly variable genes and conducted principal component analysis (PCA) for dimensionality reduction. Finally, the R package ShinyCell (v1.7.4) (<xref rid="B36" ref-type="bibr">36</xref>) was used for online visualization of the single-cell dataset.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-2">
      <title>Screening of cell-cell and gene-gene interactions</title>
      <p>The TME_Screen and SCAR_Regulon modules in SCAR predict cell-to-cell interactions and gene regulatory networks (GRNs) following the same methods used in SPEED (<xref rid="B37" ref-type="bibr">37</xref>). In brief, pySCENIC (<xref rid="B38" ref-type="bibr">38</xref>) and CellChat (<xref rid="B39" ref-type="bibr">39</xref>) were used to infer transcription factor (TF)-target regulatory networks and ligand-receptor-mediated cellular crosstalk, respectively. In the TME_Screen module, putative interactions between different cell types (e.g. T cells, B cells, fibroblasts, endothelial cells, and epithelial cells) were inferred based on known ligand-receptor pairs recorded in CellChatDB and the expression spectrum of ligands and receptors in each cell type. The process involved creating a new CellChat object from the Seurat object using the function ‘createCellChat’. Subsequently, the ligand-receptor data in CellChatDB were imported to calculate the probability of cell-to-cell communication at the ligand-receptor level using the ‘computeCommunProb’ function. The probability of cell-to-cell communication at the signaling pathway level was then determined using the ‘computeCommunProbPathway’ function, with the cell-to-cell communication network further aggregated using the ‘aggregateNet’ function. In the SCAR_Regulon module, the ‘pyscenic grn’ command was used to infer the co-expression modules of TF from single-cell expression matrix, after which ‘pyscenic ctx’ was applied for TF motif enrichment analysis and the identification of direct targets. Finally, the ‘pyscenic aucell’ command was utilized to find enrichment of regulons across single cells, followed by visualization of the interaction relationships between TFs and target genes using igraph (v1.5.1) (<xref rid="B40" ref-type="bibr">40</xref>,<xref rid="B41" ref-type="bibr">41</xref>) and ggplot2 (v3.4.3) (<xref rid="B42" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>).</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-3">
      <title>Inference of cell developmental trajectories</title>
      <p>The SCAR_Trace module provides cell differentiation state predictions, determined from scRNA-seq datasets using CytoTRACE (v0.3.3) (<xref rid="B43" ref-type="bibr">43</xref>). CytoTRACE was employed to re-construct the developmental status of different cell populations based on the single-cell expression matrix, applying a two-step prediction process. In the first step, CytoTRACE was used to calculate the Pearson correlation between the normalized expression of each gene and the gene count, generating the gene counts signature (GCS) via correlation sorting. In the second step, the normalized expression matrix was converted into a Markov matrix, with non-negative least squares regression (NNLS) applied to the GCS, which was then iteratively adjusted using a diffusion process based on the probability structure of the Markov process. The final prediction result was expressed on a scale ranging from 0 to 1, where lower values indicate a higher degree of differentiation. Finally, to visualize the cell stemness prediction results, the prediction result and the cell type information of the single cell were simultaneously applied as parameters using the ‘plotCytoTRACE’ function.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-4">
      <title>Spatial transcriptomic dataset treatment</title>
      <p>In total, 41 spatial transcriptomic datasets of 21 human, mouse and zebrafish tissues were obtained from GEO (<xref rid="B29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>), 10x Genomics (<ext-link xlink:href="https://www.10xgenomics.com/" ext-link-type="uri">https://www.10xgenomics.com/</ext-link>), SPASCER (<xref rid="B44" ref-type="bibr">44</xref>), STOmicsDB (<xref rid="B45" ref-type="bibr">45</xref>), and SODB (<xref rid="B46" ref-type="bibr">46</xref>). The spatial transcriptomic data from the SODB database were analyzed using the Python package Scanpy (v1.9.3) (<xref rid="B47" ref-type="bibr">47</xref>), while all other data were analyzed using the R package Seurat (v4.3.0) (<xref rid="B35" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>). Specifically, the ‘SCTransform’function in the R package Seurat (v4.3.0) was used to normalize gene expression matrices. Scanpy (v1.9.3) (<xref rid="B47" ref-type="bibr">47</xref>) was used to process the spatial transcriptomic datasets in the h5ad format. The built-in functions in Scanpy (v1.9.3) (‘sc.pp.normalize_total’ and ‘sc.pp.log1p’) were utilized to normalize and logarithmize the data, respectively, followed by spatial expression analysis using the ‘sc.pl.embedding’ function.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-5">
      <title>Cell type marker collection</title>
      <p>The keywords ‘cancer single-cell sequencing’ and ‘cancer cell markers’ were used separately or in combination to acquire relevant publications from the NCBI PubMed database. Text-mining of the cancer-based scRNA-seq literature was conducted to obtain cell type marker lists for distinct subpopulations of T cells (e.g. regulatory T cells, exhausted T cells, resident memory T cells, and effector memory T cells), dendritic cells (e.g. conventional dendritic cells, plasmacytoid dendritic cells, and mature dendritic cells), B cells (e.g. memory and plasma B cells), mast cells, monocytes, macrophages, neutrophils, basophils, fibroblasts, and endothelial cells. In addition to the marker gene lists, terms such as species, PMID, journal and title were also collected to provide background information of cell type markers. For each cell cluster, cell type and subtype classification information were also determined.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-6">
      <title>Cell type specific metabolic activity calculation</title>
      <p>In SCAR_Meta module, scMetabolism (<xref rid="B7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref>) and MEBOCOST (<xref rid="B48" ref-type="bibr">48</xref>) were utilized for metabolic activity quantification. For scMetabolism analysis, we first used the ‘sc.metabolism.Seurat’ function embedded in scMetabolism package to quantify activities for 85 metabolic pathways included in KEGG database (<xref rid="B49" ref-type="bibr">49</xref>) using the AUCell method. Subsequently, ‘DimPlot.metabolism’, ‘DotPlot.metabolism’, and ‘BoxPlot.metabolism’ functions were used to visualize the metabolic scores. Regarding MEBOCOST analysis, ‘mebocost.create_obj’ function was utilized to load single cell data for creating the mebocost object. Then, ‘mebo_obj.infer_commu’ function was used to infer the metabolites abundance and reconstruct metabolites communication between different cell types based on the single cell expression matrix, followed by visualization using ‘mebo_obj.eventnum_bar’, ‘mebo_obj.commun_network_plot’, ‘mebo_obj.count_dot_plot’, and ‘mebo_obj.violin_plot’.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-7">
      <title>Survival analysis</title>
      <p>The expression matrices were downloaded from The Cancer Genome Atlas (TCGA) database (<ext-link xlink:href="https://www.cancer.gov/tcga" ext-link-type="uri">https://www.cancer.gov/tcga</ext-link>) using the R package cgdsr (v1.3.0) (<ext-link xlink:href="https://libraries.io/conda/r-cgdsr" ext-link-type="uri">https://libraries.io/conda/r-cgdsr</ext-link>). Survival analysis was performed using the R package survival (v3.3.1) (<ext-link xlink:href="https://cran.r-project.org/package=survival" ext-link-type="uri">https://cran.r-project.org/package=survival</ext-link>). The survival curves of tested genes were plotted using the ‘ggsurvplot’ function in the R package survminer (v0.4.9) (<ext-link xlink:href="https://cran.r-project.org/package=survminer" ext-link-type="uri">https://cran.r-project.org/package=survminer</ext-link>).</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-8">
      <title>Tumor-specific antigen (TSA) and T cell receptor (TCR) sequence collection and cancer biomarker atlas construction</title>
      <p>Data for both TSA and TCR sequences were obtained from published literature and visualized in a table format (<xref rid="B50" ref-type="bibr">50</xref>,<xref rid="B51" ref-type="bibr">51</xref>). The TSAs were sourced from a large-scale pan-cancer study that comprehensively analyzed TCGA datasets, identifying a variety of cell surface proteins highly expressed in and specific to tumor tissues (<xref rid="B50" ref-type="bibr">50</xref>). TCR sequences of various T cell clusters were collected from multiple studies that employed TCR-seq to decipher T-cell repertoires (<xref rid="B51" ref-type="bibr">51</xref>). Biomarker information for multiple cancer types, including biomarker symbol, cancer type, body fluid type, species and tissue, were obtained from the LiqBioer database (<xref rid="B52" ref-type="bibr">52</xref>). In brief, tables were downloaded from the abovementioned sources and processed into a standard format. Each record was assigned a unique ID for efficient data management and query. Subsequently, all records in each module were integrated and stored in a csv file for download.</p>
    </sec>
  </sec>
  <sec id="SEC3">
    <title>Database content and usage</title>
    <p>The webpages of the SCAR database were designed using HTML, CSS and PHP. Data visualization was achieved using the R language, while JavaScript was used to create the interactive user interfaces. The SCAR website is currently hosted on a high-performance Linux server equipped with Apache web server packages. The database includes single-cell atlases of 11 301 352 cells from 395 cancer subtypes, as well as a spatial transcriptomic atlas of 21 tissue types. The ‘Home’ page offers users a diverse and comprehensive overview of the database and the ability to freely explore the functions of each module. On the ‘Statistics’ page, users can access and explore comprehensive data on multiomic techniques, cell numbers and cancer types available in the database. The ‘Help’ page provides extensive guidance on navigating the SCAR interface, including detailed descriptions and frame-by-frame animation demonstrations.</p>
    <p>The SCAR_ST module provides access to 41 spatial transcriptomic datasets derived from three species (human, mouse and zebrafish) (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1A</xref>), including 37 human datasets (bladder, brain, breast, intestine, kidney, large intestine, liver, lung, lymph node, ovary, pancreas, prostate, skin, stomach and uterus), three mouse datasets (lung, stomach and tail skin) and one zebrafish dataset from one tissue type (skin). Users can easily query the spatial expression patterns of specific genes in selected datasets by clicking on the anatomical labels corresponding to human, mouse and zebrafish anatomies or by searching the underlying tables individually (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>). Upon clicking an anatomical label, users are directed to an underlying table containing all genes expressed in the dataset, along with the spatial expression pattern graph and source information for the chosen gene. For example, when selecting the human lymph node tag, details of the lymphoma dataset will be displayed below. As seen in Step 4 in Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>, <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">a</xref> total of 14 674 expressed genes are available for users to explore spatial expression patterns. In Part B (Step 6 in Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>), the expression patterns of three selected genes are shown in red, green and blue, respectively. Alternatively, users can merge the three images to explore the co-expression patterns of multiple genes within the tissue context. Additionally, all images are available for download for further analysis.</p>
    <fig position="float" id="F1">
      <label>Figure 1.</label>
      <caption>
        <p>Overview of SCAR_ST module. (<bold>A</bold>) Tumor spatial transcriptomic datasets of three species included in the SCAR_ST module: i.e. human, mouse and zebrafish. (<bold>B</bold>) Selection of genes from lymphoma showcasing spatial expression patterns in the SCAR_ST module, including top 10 spatially variable genes in lymphoma (<xref rid="B56" ref-type="bibr">56</xref>). Schematics were created with BioRender.com.</p>
      </caption>
      <graphic xlink:href="gkad753fig1" position="float"/>
    </fig>
    <p>The SCAR_Atlas module contains four types of cancer single-cell atlases, including human, mouse, organoids and cell lines, covering 523 scRNA-seq datasets across 395 cancer subtypes (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2A</xref>). Users can first query the scRNA-seq datasets using the ‘Advanced search’ button at the top of the page, either individually or in combination with multiple criteria. Users can filter datasets of interest based on species, published journals, cancer types, sample tissues, disease systems, cell types, sequencing technologies and cell numbers (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>). Upon clicking the ‘Apply search’ button, the search results are displayed in the table below. Users can reset their selection at any time by clicking the ‘Reset’ button next to the ‘Apply search’ button. Within each cancer atlas, users have several options for searching the single-cell datasets. These include making a hierarchical selection in the column, clicking on the image of corresponding cancer subtype, or selecting the relevant name from a word cloud. The resulting table below will display information on the datasets, including cell information, gene expression, graph visualizations and data sources, which can be further queried using the ShinyCell links (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>). For example, users can initiate a search in the hierarchical selection of the single-cell atlas of human cancer and opt for colorectal cancer. From the six subtypes that then appear, they can further select the microsatellite stable (MSS) colorectal cancer subtype and obtain the dataset ID, with the SCAR_Atlas_0790 dataset (<xref rid="B53" ref-type="bibr">53</xref>) subsequently presented in the table below (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>). On the ‘Detail’ page, users will find a comprehensive list of information related to the SCAR_Atlas_0790 dataset, including cancer type classification, number of cells in the dataset, specific cell types included and article from which the data originated (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>). On the ‘ShinyCell’ page of the SCAR_Atlas_0790 dataset, users can access seven sections to visualize gene expression profiles and cell type information for genes, including cell information and gene expression on the low dimension, gene co-expression of any two genes, violin plots/boxplots of different cell types, proportion plots of cell types composition and bubble plots/heatmaps of up to 50 gene expression patterns.</p>
    <fig position="float" id="F2">
      <label>Figure 2.</label>
      <caption>
        <p>Demonstration of SCAR_Atlas module. (<bold>A</bold>) Cancer scRNA-seq datasets in SCAR_Atlas module from four sources: i.e. human, mouse, organoids and cell lines. (<bold>B</bold>) Procedures for accessing dataset information and single-cell atlas of a colorectal cancer dataset in the SCAR_Atlas module (<xref rid="B53" ref-type="bibr">53</xref>). Schematics were created with BioRender.com.</p>
      </caption>
      <graphic xlink:href="gkad753fig2" position="float"/>
    </fig>
    <p>Understanding tumor cell diversity and identifying molecular markers for different cell populations within the tumor ecosystem are essential for evaluating dynamic and intricate cellular interactions during T cell exhaustion, cancer cell metastasis, and immune evasion. As important components of the cancer microenvironment, immune cells, endothelial cells and fibroblasts consist of diverse populations with distinct phenotypes and functions. Therefore, the construction of a systematic molecular atlas of cancer cell clusters should enhance our ability to develop early cancer detection strategies, evaluate anti-tumor immunotherapies and clarify the regulatory mechanisms underlying tumor progression and metastasis (<xref rid="B54" ref-type="bibr">54</xref>). The SCAR_CT module consists of 10 cell types within the tumor microenvironment, namely, T cells, B cells, dendritic cells, monocytes, macrophages, neutrophils, basophils, mast cells, fibroblasts and endothelial cells (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3A</xref>). By selecting the image of the cell type of interest, users gain access to further information regarding the cell type, including the number of each cell subtype and dataset details through a doughnut chart. By clicking on the green ‘Details’ button, users can also track the source of the dataset (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3A</xref>). For example, selecting the ‘Treg’ cell from the ‘T cell’ category yields a total of 18 records, from which users can obtain specific details, such as cell markers for non-small cell lung cancer in the SCAR_CT_000036 dataset (<xref rid="B55" ref-type="bibr">55</xref>).</p>
    <fig position="float" id="F3">
      <label>Figure 3.</label>
      <caption>
        <p>Overview of SCAR_CT and SCAR_Meta modules. (<bold>A</bold>) Procedures for accessing and downloading cell biomarker information related to Treg cells in non-small cell lung cancer in the SCAR_CT module (<xref rid="B55" ref-type="bibr">55</xref>). (<bold>B</bold>) Procedures for observing metabolic activity within the MSS colorectal cancer dataset in the SCAR_Meta module (<xref rid="B53" ref-type="bibr">53</xref>). Schematics were created with BioRender.com.</p>
      </caption>
      <graphic xlink:href="gkad753fig3" position="float"/>
    </fig>
    <p>The various functional modules within the SCAR database can be utilized in an integrated manner to reveal insights into tumor biology. For instance, in the SCAR_ST module (Part B function), users can search for specific markers, namely, <italic toggle="yes">FOXP3</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">TNFRSF9</italic> and <italic toggle="yes">CTLA4</italic> (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>), with the spatial distribution of Treg cells in the SCAR_ST_000001 dataset (<xref rid="B56" ref-type="bibr">56</xref>) able to be confirmed based on the merged expression patterns of the Treg markers. In the SCAR_Atlas module, users can also apply cell markers to identify the gene expression of specific cell types within the scRNA-seq datasets. For instance, when investigating SCAR_Atlas_0790 dataset (<xref rid="B53" ref-type="bibr">53</xref>) of human colorectal cancer, gene expression of the CD8 exhausted T (CD8Tex) cell markers, <italic toggle="yes">HAVCR2</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">CXCL13</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">PDCD1</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">TOX</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">IFNG</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">GZMB</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">MIR155HG</italic> and <italic toggle="yes">ITGAE</italic>, can be identified in the dataset heatmap, thus revealing specific and significant expression patterns of exhaustion signatures (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>).</p>
    <p>The SCAR_Meta module allows users to screen the metabolic features of every unique cell type in the SCAR_Atlas, covering all cancer types in 28 categories (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3B</xref>). After selecting a specific cancer type for searching, all cancer subtypes included in that cancer type will be listed in the following table. By clicking the ‘click’ button in the table, users can access a series of plots displaying the metabolic pathways of all cell types within the dataset (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3B</xref>). Users can freely download all graphs by selecting the ‘Download’ button in the image section. As shown in Step 5 in Figure 3B, Tprolif cells (proliferating T cells) from MSS colorectal cancer in the SCAR_Atlas_0790 dataset (<xref rid="B53" ref-type="bibr">53</xref>) exhibited higher activity in three metabolic pathways (fatty acid elongation, fatty acid degradation and butanoate metabolism) compared to other cell types (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3B</xref>).</p>
    <p>The SCAR_Survival module plots the survival curve for each tested gene across 31 cancer types. To view the survival curve for a specific gene, users can select the corresponding gene symbol from the table, categorized by cancer type in eight system categories. By clicking the ‘small eye’ icon in the ‘View Survival Curve’ column, the survival curve for the selected gene in the corresponding cancer type will be displayed below (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4A</xref>).</p>
    <fig position="float" id="F4">
      <label>Figure 4.</label>
      <caption>
        <p>Illustrations of usage of SCAR_Survival and BM_Atlas modules. (<bold>A</bold>) Procedures for visualizing survival curve of a transcription factor for glioblastoma multiforme in the SCAR_Survival module ((<xref rid="B59" ref-type="bibr">59</xref>), 10x Genomics sample data <ext-link xlink:href="https://support.10xgenomics.com/spatial-gene-expression/datasets/1.2.0/Targeted_Visium_Human_Glioblastoma_Pan_Cancer" ext-link-type="uri">https://support.10xgenomics.com/spatial-gene-expression/datasets/1.2.0/Targeted_Visium_Human_Glioblastoma_Pan_Cancer</ext-link>). (<bold>B</bold>) Procedures for retrieving biomarker expression patterns from a gastric cancer dataset in the BM_Atlas module (<xref rid="B57" ref-type="bibr">57</xref>). Schematics were created with BioRender.com.</p>
      </caption>
      <graphic xlink:href="gkad753fig4" position="float"/>
    </fig>
    <p>The TME_Screen module serves as a tool for exploring cellular crosstalk within the tumor microenvironment, enabling users to access predicted cell communication between ligands and corresponding receptors in different cell types in the human and mouse single-cell atlases. The TME_Screen module also provides users with the opportunity to visualize the interactions and signaling pathways between cell types by hierarchically selecting species, cancer type, cancer subtype and dataset ID in the column (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Figure S1A</xref>). Furthermore, users can also search for keywords in the table at the bottom, which provides a comprehensive overview of ligand–receptor interactions and related signaling pathways among all cell types, thus allowing users to obtain customized cellular information (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Figure S1A</xref>).</p>
    <p>Traditionally, biomarkers were identified based on their distinct expression patterns between cancer tissues and controls. However, the identification of the cell types that most abundantly express these cancer biomarker genes remains largely undetermined, primarily due to the complex cellular composition of tumor tissues. The BM_Atlas module addresses this issue by collecting a diverse range of cancer biomarkers from the LiqBioer database (<xref rid="B52" ref-type="bibr">52</xref>), facilitating subsequent screening of expression heterogeneity within the tumor microenvironment. To utilize this module, users can first choose a specific scRNA-seq dataset by hierarchically selecting species, cancer type, subtype and dataset ID. Upon selecting a cancer subtype, a category of biomarkers is presented (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4B</xref>), from which users can choose a specific biomarker gene of interest. The module will then generate the expression pattern of the selected biomarker at the bottom. For example, if the user selects the human gastric cancer scRNA-seq dataset SCAR_Atlas_0003 (<xref rid="B57" ref-type="bibr">57</xref>) and the specific gastric cancer biomarker <italic toggle="yes">MUC1</italic>, they will observe almost exclusive expression of <italic toggle="yes">MUC1</italic> in a pit mucous cell cluster PMC_c6 (Figure <xref rid="F4" ref-type="fig">4B</xref>).</p>
    <p>The SCAR_Regulon module allows users to screen the genetic regulatory networks of different cell types in the human and mouse cancer scRNA-seq datasets. Users can query gene regulatory networks (<xref rid="B38" ref-type="bibr">38</xref>) and GO term enrichment analysis of candidate target genes of each regulon by hierarchically selecting species, cancer type, cancer subtype, dataset ID, and cell type (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Figure S1B</xref>).</p>
    <p>In the SCAR_Trace module, users can explore the prediction of differentiation states based on scRNA-seq datasets. Upon the hierarchical selection of a specific cancer type from the top bar, the module presents a series of visualizations. Firstly, a CytoTRACE_plot graph will showcase the predicted degree of differentiation for that cell type. Secondly, another graph will offer a more detailed view of the differentiation extent of each cell type. Thirdly, a bar chart will provide a visual representation of the correlation between genes and differentiation states. Finally, a table will provide more comprehensive information (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Figure S2</xref> (<xref rid="B58" ref-type="bibr">58</xref>)). The last two modules (SCAR_TSA and SCAR_TCR) enable users to screen TSAs (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5A</xref>) and acquire TCR distribution for different T cell populations (Figure <xref rid="F5" ref-type="fig">5B</xref>). Additionally, we provided pan-cancer analysis to allow users to investigate the similarities and differences of gene expression patterns among multiple cancer types and pan-survival analysis in which users can query and compare the survival curves of a specific gene among multiple cancer types.</p>
    <fig position="float" id="F5">
      <label>Figure 5.</label>
      <caption>
        <p>Illustrations of usage of SCAR_TSA (<bold>A</bold>) (<xref rid="B50" ref-type="bibr">50</xref>) and SCAR_TCR (<bold>B</bold>) modules (<xref rid="B51" ref-type="bibr">51</xref>).</p>
      </caption>
      <graphic xlink:href="gkad753fig5" position="float"/>
    </fig>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="conclusions" id="SEC4">
    <title>Conclusions and future development</title>
    <p>To date, various platforms have been developed to explore cancer single-cell sequencing data, each with a unique focus. For example, CancerSEA aims to decode the functional states of cancer cells, whereas CancerSCEM seeks to investigate the cancer microenvironment. In contrast, SCAR represents a comprehensive and accessible resource for the integrative discovery and analysis of spatially resolved and single-cell transcriptomic data in the context of cancer. This powerful platform was designed to facilitate deep exploration of tumor cell heterogeneity and holds great potential for advancing cancer immunotherapy research. Firstly, the database offers a comprehensive map for analyzing cancer cell metastasis and invasion by combining spatial transcriptomic data with single-cell sequencing data. Secondly, SCAR currently hosts an extensive collection of cancer subtypes, including spatial transcriptomic data from 21 tissue types across three species and single-cell gene expression datasets encompassing 11 301 352 cells across 395 cancer subtypes. Thirdly, SCAR contains diverse functional modules, providing users with multiple visualization and analysis capabilities. Notably, differential analysis between different cell types allows users to explore different aspects of the cancer microenvironment and develop gene expression patterns of specific cell types. The integration of spatial and single-cell transcriptomic data, along with comprehensive analysis functions, allows users to systematically evaluate the tumor microenvironment and immune responses. Thus, this unique combination of features makes SCAR a valuable resource for researchers seeking a deeper understanding of cancer biology and immunology.</p>
    <p>It should be mentioned that, in the current version of the SCAR database, different annotation standards were applied to different data sets according to the original publication, and this might affect the comparability of results. A standard pipeline to process the raw sequencing data might solve this problem in the future. Moving forward, the SCAR online platform will undergo further development to provide more user-friendly interfaces, integrated features, and web-based tools. Additionally, more cancer omics data will be collected and stored in the database. Currently, SCAR primarily focuses on single-cell transcriptomic and spatial transcriptomic data analysis. The integration of genomic (whole genome sequencing, whole exome sequencing, genome-wide association studies) and epigenetic data (the assay for transposase-accessible chromatin with sequencing, chromatin immunoprecipitation followed by sequencing, Hi-C) will provide insights into the mutation profiles and regulatory landscapes of different cancer types. Moreover, we aim to strengthen and expand pan-cancer analysis in SCAR to reveal the common regulatory mechanisms and potential therapeutic targets shared among different cancers.</p>
  </sec>
